SIMPLE: overcast
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overcast
<hw>O`ver*cast"</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧`v⟦etil⟧r*k⟦adot⟧st")</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cast or cover over; hence, to cloud; to
darken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those clouds that <qex>overcast</qex> your morn shall fly.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To compute or rate too high.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Sewing)</fld> <def>To take long, loose stitches
over (the raw edges of a seam) to prevent raveling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bookbinding)</fld> <def>To fasten, as single
sheets, by overcast stitching or by folding one edge over
another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overcast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: overcast
<hw>o`ver*cast"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Meteorology)</fld> <def>Completely or almost completely covered
over with clouds; -- of the sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Sewing)</fld> <def>Sewn by overcasting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overcatch</ent>⟦br⟧
